{"key":"processedPost-9892793","value":{"id":9892793,"first":9892164,"last":9894112,"when":1235964837,"utime":"03/02/09 05:33 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Akira4321 said:</strong><br />I keep reading such good things about Martha's but when I talk about them in #cultivation a few people say their not a good idea because of contamination concerns. So is this a good option for a high output setup or no? </blockquote><br />If a noob made a mini-greenhouse and got contamination, it's his fault not the greenhouse.&nbsp; He'd have said the same about any other form of fruiting chamber as well so as not to blame himself for screwing something up.&nbsp; Contamination is caused by faulty technique, not the greenhouse or FC.<br />The only purpose of a fruiting environment is to provide an area with high humidity, light, and lots of fresh air.&nbsp; Personally, I don't use Martha's because they're too small.&nbsp; I make my own mini-greenhouses out of PVC tubing and plastic sheeting, so they can go from floor to ceiling and from wall to wall across my available space.&nbsp; Whatever you use, cut lots of holes in it for natural circulation of fresh air, and then either put your humidifier inside the greenhouse or pipe it in with 4\" clothes dryer hose so you don't create back pressure that will ruin your humidifier.<br />RR","title":"Re: Martha's Good Or Bad"}}